<TITLE> Platini makes winning team step up for trophy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 VIENNA, June 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The winners of Sunday's Euro 2008 final between Germany and Spain will be handed the Henri Delaunay Trophy in the stadium's main stand as part of a return to tradition favoured by UEFA president Michel Platini. UEFA spokesman Rob Faulkner told a news conference before the match that it had been Platini's personal wish for the winning team to climb the steps to pick up the trophy, just as players did during Platini's own days captaining France. "Mr Platini engineered the change because he liked the more traditional approach of the players being tired after the game but making that last effort to go up and get the cup," Faulkner said. Platini, who became UEFA president last year, led France up the steps of the Parc des Princes stadium in Paris in 1984 after clinching the European title on home soil with a 2-0 final win over Spain. In 2000, when France again lifted the trophy, the ceremony was moved to the pitch for a more television-friendly celebration complete with confetti cannons. Greece also received the 2004 trophy on the pitch
